Lizeka Tandwa, News24An ANC supporter dances at FNB Stadium. (AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg - The African National Congress in Johannesburg is making attempts to solicit support from the Economic Freedom Fighters in council matters that affect the poor, it said on Tuesday."We are not in discussion with the EFF on a coalition, but we have had a meeting with EFF around issues that pertain to our programmes, which we think are programmes that are pro-poor," Johannesburg ANC regional secretary Dada Morero told journalists.The two parties had agreed to hold follow-up meetings in 2017.Morero said the parties had agreed to present their issues and begin to collaborate in the DA-run council. The ANC was also trying to engage with the Inkatha Freedom Party on a possible collaboration in council.READ: Mashaba, Makhura agree to put differences asideShortly after the August 3 local government elections, EFF leader Julius Malema said his party would vote with the DA in hung councils. Given the choice between it and the ANC, it was the better of two devils, he said.Malema said the party would not enter into coalitions with any party in any municipality in the country, but would vote with certain parties in various councils.The EFF voted for Mashaba as mayor of Johannesburg, despite its misgivings, Malema said in August. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.